Note that having validation group sequences means that as soon as one of the groups defined in the sequence generates at least one constraint violation, no further groups will be processed. With that said, one way to approach this could be:

Add groups to your constraints: 

    class User {
    	@NotBlank                                               // leave in the default group
    	@Email(regexp = &quot;.*@email.com&quot;, groups = Second.class)  // need to have a group to put it in the &quot;second round&quot; of validation
    	@UniqueEmail(groups = Third.class)                      // need to have a group to put it in the &quot;third round&quot; of validation
    	private String email;
    
    	@NotBlank                       // leave in the default group
    	@Length(min = 8)                // leave in the default group
    	private String password;
    
    	public User(String email, String password) {
    		this.email = email;
    		this.password = password;
    	}
    }

and then define your sequences as:

    @GroupSequence({Default.class, Second.class, Third.class})
    interface UserCreateValidationGroupSequence {}
    
    @GroupSequence({Default.class, Second.class})
    interface UserUpdateValidationGroupSequence {}

and then you&#39;d pass either create or update sequence to the validator, in your case, it could be:

    @Service
    public class UserService {
    	public void addUser(@Validated(UserCreateValidationGroupSequence.class) User user){...}
    	public void updateUser(@Validated(UserUpdateValidationGroupSequence.class) User user){...}
    }

Now, if you&#39;d like to keep the `updateUser()` service call without passing the specific group(sequence) and only mark it with `@Valid/@Validated` you can consider looking at default group sequence redefinition. In such case, you&#39;d add the default (update) sequence definition to your class:

    @GroupSequence({User.class, Second.class})
    class User {
    	@NotBlank                                               // leave in the default group
    	@Email(regexp = &quot;.*@email.com&quot;, groups = Second.class)  // need to have a group to put it in the &quot;second round&quot; of validation
    	@UniqueEmail(groups = Third.class)                      // need to have a group to put it in the &quot;third round&quot; of validation
    	private String email;
    
    	@NotBlank                       // leave in the default group
    	@Length(min = 8)                // leave in the default group
    	private String password;
    
    }

have the create sequence:

    @GroupSequence({Default.class, Second.class, Third.class})
    interface UserCreateValidationGroupSequence {}

and finally, in service:

    @Service
    public class UserService {
    	public void addUser(@Validated(UserCreateValidationGroupSequence.class) User user){...}
    	public void updateUser(@Valid User user){...}
    }

