First of all, I think your first tag is wrong. You are talking about **JavaScript**, right?

I am not sure to fully understand your question, but if you want to get the **SVG** code behind a chart, you have to make sure that developers you work with do not use the **Canvas** API.

**Echarts** has two renderers: `canvas` and `svg`. See [Canvas vs. SVG - Best Practices - Handbook - Apache ECharts][1]. If you want to use the **SVG renderer**, charts should be [initialized][2] like this:

```javascript
let myChart = echarts.init(document.getElementById(&#39;main&#39;), null, { renderer: &#39;svg&#39; });
```

Now, to export your chart to SVG, you can:

 - Configure the **toolbox** (see [`toolbox.feature.saveAsImage.type`][3]). A download button will appear in the top right corner of the main container.
 - Copy/paste the code using **browser developer tools**.

Here is an example ([JSFiddle][4]):

```javascript
let option = {
  toolbox: {
    feature: {
      saveAsImage: {
        type: &#39;svg&#39; // &lt;--- HERE
      }
    }
  },
  xAxis: {
    type: &#39;category&#39;,
    data: [&#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;C&#39;]
  },
  yAxis: {
    type: &#39;value&#39;
  },
  series: [
    {
      data: [10, 20, 15],
      type: &#39;bar&#39;
    }
  ]
};

let myChart = echarts.init(document.getElementById(&#39;main&#39;), null, { renderer: &#39;svg&#39; });
myChart.setOption(option);
```

